Verdict: The template is strong at defining truthful governance and artifact shapes, but still materially underpowered at the execution layer for downstream adopters. Today it mostly gives downstream repos contracts, generators, and a few narrow audits; it does not yet give them enough runnable wrappers, proof-producing validators, and orchestration surfaces to show that the declared design was actually executable in that repository.

| Priority | Proposal | Solves | Why current support is insufficient | Suggested surface | Adoption tier | Governance risk |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| P1 | Adoption proof bundle and verifier | Lets a downstream repo prove it adopted the framework honestly, with concrete evidence instead of a narrative claim | `scripts/validate_template.py` for adopters mainly checks expected files plus some structure; it does not emit a durable adoption receipt showing which mechanisms were actually wired, which commands were verified, which CLI reviewers ran, and which gaps remain | Add `scripts/adoption_verifier.py` plus `templates/adoption_receipt.template.md` and a runbook section in [docs/STRICT_ADOPTION_AND_VERIFICATION.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/docs/STRICT_ADOPTION_AND_VERIFICATION.md). It should collect validator results, toolchain probe results, reviewer outputs, capability flags, missing mechanisms, and output `fully adopted` / `partially adopted` / `design-only upgrade path kept` with evidence links | Mandatory for strict adopters | Low if it only certifies evidence; high if it self-upgrades status without explicit gap reporting |
| P2 | Developer Toolchain probe runner with freshness receipts | Stops downstream agents from saying “the template asked for run/health/repro surfaces but gave no way to verify them” | [docs/DEVELOPER_TOOLCHAIN_DESIGN.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/docs/DEVELOPER_TOOLCHAIN_DESIGN.md) defines status semantics well, but there is no shipped tool that probes declared commands, records outcomes, and updates trust state. Current validation is structural, not operational | Add `scripts/developer_toolchain_probe.py`, `templates/developer_toolchain_receipt.template.md`, and manifest wiring so adopters can run `probe diagnostics/build/run/health/repro`. The tool should check command existence, execute allowed probes, capture exit status and timestamp, and write receipts that justify `verified-working` or `known-broken` | Mandatory for standard/full; profile-gated for minimal | Medium if it auto-edits project-context statuses directly; safer if it writes receipts and requires human promotion into canonical status |
| P3 | Task lifecycle wrapper that enforces packet/receipt/sync/closeout sequencing | Removes the gap between “these artifacts exist” and “agents actually have a concrete runner that tells them when to create them” | Current pipeline scripts are separate generators: [scripts/git_audit_pipeline.py](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/scripts/git_audit_pipeline.py), [scripts/state_sync_pipeline.py](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/scripts/state_sync_pipeline.py), and [scripts/closeout_truth_audit.py](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/scripts/closeout_truth_audit.py). They do not form one execution loop or scheduler | Add `scripts/task_control.py` that can `init-task`, `checkpoint`, `block`, `handoff`, `pre-closeout`, and `closeout-ready`. It should read the task packet, enforce presence of required artifacts before each transition, and run the existing sync/closeout audits automatically | Mandatory for repos claiming multi-step or multi-executor support | Medium if it becomes a rigid runtime that overrides repo-specific judgment; keep it as a bounded state machine, not a full autonomous orchestrator |
| P4 | CLI review dispatcher and normalized independent-evaluation packet | Makes independent review executable instead of a policy expectation that varies by machine and chat memory | [docs/runbooks/multi-model-discussion-loop.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/docs/runbooks/multi-model-discussion-loop.md) and [docs/STRICT_ADOPTION_AND_VERIFICATION.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/docs/STRICT_ADOPTION_AND_VERIFICATION.md) require local multi-CLI review, but the template intentionally avoids standardizing commands. That preserves portability, but leaves downstream repos without a concrete review runner | Add a machine-local executor registry in project context or manifest plus `scripts/review_dispatch.py` that dispatches the same prompt read-only to declared executors, stores raw outputs, normalizes severity labels, and appends a synthesis-ready packet | Mandatory for strict adoption claims; optional otherwise | Medium if normalized summaries erase dissent. Preserve raw outputs and make synthesis append-only |
| P5 | Skill host wrapper contract and invocation runner | Prevents downstream repos from keeping SKILL governance docs without any realistic way to invoke skills and emit runtime evidence | [docs/SKILL_EXECUTION_LAYER_V1_DRAFT.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/docs/SKILL_EXECUTION_LAYER_V1_DRAFT.md) defines host integration and receipts, but [scripts/skill_evolution_pipeline.py](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/scripts/skill_evolution_pipeline.py) only writes artifacts after the fact. It does not help a downstream agent decide `invoke or skip`, load references, bind tools, or record invocation truth automatically | Add `scripts/skill_runner.py`, `templates/skill_registry.template.yaml`, and validator rules that each non-knowledge skill declares its execution binding: trigger evaluator, required references, toolchain surface, receipt output path, degradation path. The runner should emit invocation receipts directly from execution | Profile-gated: mandatory when adopters keep SKILL surfaces, optional otherwise | High if it drifts into self-mutating skill automation. Keep candidate creation separate from canonical mutation |
| P6 | Execution readiness audit across project-context, command existence, user surfaces, and runtime guard bindings | Makes failure states auditable before real work begins | Current adopter validation does not answer “is this repo execution-ready?” It cannot prove that declared toolchain commands exist, user-surface map entries map to real paths, runtime evidence sources exist, or runtime guard registries cover sensitive surfaces | Add `scripts/execution_readiness_audit.py` that cross-checks project-context commands, referenced files, smoke/repro paths, runtime evidence entries, sensitive surfaces, and optional runtime guard registry coverage; emit a receipt with pass/warn/fail per surface | Mandatory for standard/full; optional for minimal | Low if it reports gaps only; medium if it hard-fails repos that are honestly incomplete but clearly labeled |
| P7 | Evidence recency and stale-status audit | Prevents old “verified-working” claims from becoming permanent fiction | The toolchain design names status values, but there is no freshness rule or audit for stale `verified-working` entries. A downstream repo can honestly bootstrap once and then silently decay | Add `scripts/evidence_freshness_audit.py` tied to probe receipts, adoption receipts, and review packets. It should flag stale runtime statuses, old repro claims, and expired independent-review evidence for strict adoption assertions | Optional for minimal; mandatory for strict/full | Low if it only downgrades confidence and opens a gap; risky if it silently rewrites canonical statuses |
| P8 | Failure-packet and root-cause generation wrapper tied to sensitive surface escalation | Makes runtime failure handling executable and auditable instead of depending on agents remembering to open the right artifact | The template has failure and root-cause templates plus security escalation guidance in [templates/project-context.template.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/templates/project-context.template.md), but no concrete generator that opens the right artifact when a sensitive user surface or guardrail fails | Add `scripts/failure_capture.py` that takes impacted surface, evidence source, sensitivity, and suspected cause; generates a failure packet or root-cause note and links it to task and closeout receipts | Profile-gated for repos with live runtime paths | Medium if it encourages premature cause claims. Require explicit `cause-suspected` vs `cause-established` states |

Recommended next move: Build one tight “execution proof” wave before adding more philosophy: `adoption_verifier.py`, `developer_toolchain_probe.py`, `task_control.py`, and `review_dispatch.py`. Those four additions would give downstream repos a concrete way to prove mechanism adoption, verify their declared runtime surfaces, enforce the core packet/receipt loop, and produce independent review artifacts. That is the shortest path to making downstream agents less able to blame the template for missing execution support while preserving the current governance boundary.
